				<div class="postbody">
				</span><table width="90%" cellspacing="1" cellpadding="3" border="0" align="center"><tr> 	  <td><span class="genmed"><b>Quote:</b></span></td>	</tr>	<tr>	  <td class="quote"> Police are nothing but citizens themselves. There is nothing against the law using an informant. </td>	</tr></table><span class="postbody">
<br />

<br />
There's nothing against using an informant, but that isn't what you are talking about. These are people trained by law enforcement and given authority (alongside which comes the requirement) to search people's homes. They are the police, in the eyes of the law. When a police officer comes to your door without a warrant, you are totally within your rights to not let him in if you don't want to. Letting him in is tacit permission for him to "search" your home; anything in plain view is considered fair game. He can't go through your closets without additional permission, but if you have a baggie of weed sitting out on a desk, he can bust you no problem. Where is the option to let in an exterminator or cable guy so that he can do the work he is there for, but without him doing an equivalent search? There isn't any. That's *far* too grey. No court would allow such a law to stand, and any evidence would be thrown out, period.
<br />

<br />
edit- Ohyea, police officers are NOT considered the same thing as civilians, in a number of ways. Your friend can go through your dresser, find drugs, and bring them to the police, and you get busted. If the police did the EXACT same thing with no warrant, the evidence gets tossed.<br />
				<span class="gensmall"></span><br />
				</div>
			</td></tr>
