He can go through your closets if you do not explicitly object.  He can walk into your house without a warrant the same way.  If your door is not locked a warrant is not neccessary.  Your failure to secure your home is permission for entry, after all the officer just came over for a friendly neighborly visit and there you were with your @#%$ lover in texas thinking you had some privacy.
<br />

<br />
About the weed: Not in my state they can't.  Californias law is written to make it impossible for police to bust people for personal amounts of marijuana.  Thank god.  and thank god for the 9th Circut Court of Appeals smacking down the feds from subverting state law.
<br />

<br />
</span><table width="90%" cellspacing="1" cellpadding="3" border="0" align="center"><tr> 	  <td><span class="genmed"><b>Quote:</b></span></td>	</tr>	<tr>	  <td class="quote">Where is the option to let in an exterminator or cable guy so that he can do the work he is there for, but without him doing an equivalent search? There isn't any. That's *far* too grey. No court would allow such a law to stand, and any evidence would be thrown out, period.</td>	</tr></table><span class="postbody">
<br />

<br />
I suppose you could make them sign a confidentiality and non-disclosure agreement holding them liable for a $200,000 fee for divulging any of what the see, hear or experience.
<br />

<br />
Most of the people that work for the police are civilians There is one big difference in police and civilians and that is whether or not they are a "sworn officer of the law".  These bugmen will be like a community watch group in such matters.
<br />

<br />
These people are a special group.  They are not held to the same strict rules of evidenciary procedure at all that sworn officers are.  Just being trained by the police in a "community outreach" program does not make you sworn.  Community watch groups do not have any affect on evidence in federal courts.  They are just community concious people. I believe some larger cities and maybe some states have laws that restrict their activities.  Most do not.
<br />

<br />
Bugmen and the Cableguy would be regular people with some special understanding about what is an important piece of information.  They would simply be "keeping their eyes open" and collecting the rewards whenever their hunch is right.
<br />

<br />
The shame in my eyes is that the supreme court long ago limited the protection of citizens to only being safe from the sworn police in such matters.  You would think that evidence illegally attained is illegally attained; But, no.  You need kick %@$# lawyers for that kind of defense.<br />
