<br />
</td>	</tr></table><span class="postbody">
<br />

<br />
Police ARE NOT considered citizens while on duty.  While using informants is legal, there are strict, strict rules regulating the practice.  Even if the rules are followed exactly, some judges can throw out evidence if they feel something is amiss.
<br />

<br />
</span><table width="90%" cellspacing="1" cellpadding="3" border="0" align="center"><tr> 	  <td><span class="genmed"><b>poppa wrote:</b></span></td>	</tr>	<tr>	  <td class="quote">
<br />
Matter of fact, if a bugman breaks the law to get evidence then "hands it over" to the the police, the fact that the agency didn't break the law to get it makes it admissable.
<br />

<br />
The law does not stop police from doing this sort of thing right now.  It's always been legal to do.  It has been so repugnant to people that most police wouldn't dare do such a thing.</td>	</tr></table><span class="postbody">
<br />

<br />

<br />
This is not legal to do; it is a clear violation of the 4th Amendment.  Just because police officers themselves don't do the actual searching doesn't mean it's legal for them to do it by proxy.
<br />

<br />
There are certain tests that searches have to pass in order to be constitutional.  If you're growing weed in your backyard and you have a 10-foot fence that blocks all view into the yard, it's not legal for a police officer to peak over the fence to discover the pot.  However, if they fly overhead in a helicopter or plane, then it's perfectly legal, because any ordinary citizen could fly over your house and see the marijuana plants from above.  "Plain view" and "open field" are terms frequently used when 4th Amendment rights are put in question.
<br />

<br />
Now, if you invite someone into your house and you have a stockpile of guns laid out on your coffee table and they see it, they can report that to the police, FBI or ATF.  However, once that tip is given to police, they must obtain a search warrant to conduct the search.  If neither the tip nor the credibility of the informant is sufficient, then a warrant can be denied at minimum and if the warrant is granted, the defense can later challenge the legality of the evidence obtained from the warrant at worst.
<br />

<br />
This program is a legal nightmare waiting to happen.<br />
				<span class="gensmall"></span><br />
				</div>
			</td></tr>
		</table>
		</td>
	</tr>
