		<td class="row1" width="100%" height="28" valign="top">

		<table width="100%" border="0" cellspacing="0" cellpadding="0">
			<tr>
			<td><table width="100%" border="0" cellspacing="0" cellpadding="0"><tr><td width="100%"><a href="viewtopic.php?p=76293&amp;sid=a143b8d25b5cebafd65ac72d231635ff#76293"><img src="templates/eqluclin/images/icon_minipost.gif" width="12" height="9" alt="Post" title="Post" border="0" /></a><span class="postdetails">Posted: Thu Jul 22, 2004 4:00 pm<span class="gen">&nbsp;</span>&nbsp; &nbsp;Post subject: Re: Bugman gets a new job</span></td>
				<td width="30%" valign="top" nowrap="nowrap" align="right"> <a href="posting.php?mode=quote&amp;p=76293&amp;sid=a143b8d25b5cebafd65ac72d231635ff"><img src="templates/eqluclin/images/lang_english/icon_quote.gif" alt="Reply with quote" title="Reply with quote" border="0" /></a>   </td></tr></table></td>
			</tr>
			<tr><td colspan="2"><hr /></td></tr>
			<tr><td colspan="2">
				<div class="postbody">
				</span><table width="90%" cellspacing="1" cellpadding="3" border="0" align="center"><tr> 	  <td><span class="genmed"><b>poppa wrote:</b></span></td>	</tr>	<tr>	  <td class="quote">
<br />

<br />
He can go through your closets if you do not explicitly object.  He can walk into your house without a warrant the same way.  If your door is not locked a warrant is not neccessary.  Your failure to secure your home is permission for entry, after all the officer just came over for a friendly neighborly visit and there you were with your @#%$ lover in texas thinking you had some privacy.
<br />

<br />
</td>	</tr></table><span class="postbody">
<br />

<br />
Wrong and wrong.  I don't know what country you live in.  Depending on the circumstances of why the police are there, they simply cannot open doors and start rummaging through your belongings.  If contraband is in "plain view," then they can use that as evidence against you.  If the contraband is behind a closed door with absolutely no reason for the officer to open it, then they cannot open it.  
<br />

<br />
Police can't walk into your unlocked house for no reason just to look for things.  Even an unlocked house retains privacy rights.  There is still the requirement of probable cause.  If a cop opens your door to welcome you to the neighborhood (on duty that's not likely to happen) and sees you snorting a huge line of coke, he can arrest you, but none of that evidence can be used against you, since he had no legal reason for being inside your house.  He invaded your privacy, plain and simple.   Even if you were doing something illegal, you still have rights.
<br />

<br />
If you are not under arrest, the officer <span style="font-weight: bold">MUST</span> ask your permission to search first.  He can still go ahead and search you and your possessions after that (and usually only after arresting you), but he has to have a damn good reason, otherwise anything he finds to use against you will be thrown out in court.<br />
				<span class="gensmall"></span><br />
				</div>
			</td></tr>
		</table>
